# @vef-framework-react/approval-form-bridge

Projection bridge from `@vef-framework-react/form-editor` schemas to the approval form contract
(`approval/form_field.go` in the Go backend â€” a bare `ApprovalFormField[]`, no wrapper object), plus the
approval capability profile for the designer. Deploy sends the rich schema verbatim
(`DeployFlowCmd.FormSchema`); the backend derives the flat field list itself via its
`internal/approval/formeditor` parser â€” the enforcement-side twin of `projectFormSchema`, kept in
lockstep through the golden fixtures under `src/__fixtures__/formeditor-parity/`.

## Installation

```bash
pnpm add @vef-framework-react/approval-form-bridge
```

## Usage

```tsx
import {
  createApprovalRegistries,
  projectFormSchema,
  validateApprovalSchema
} from "@vef-framework-react/approval-form-bridge";

// 1. Design under the approval profile (no switch / daterange / button).
//    The registries prop is honored on first mount only â€” keep one instance.
const [registries] = useState(createApprovalRegistries);
<FormEditor registries={registries} onSchemaChange={setSchema} />;

// 2. One projection feeds every designer-side consumer (deploy itself sends
//    the rich schema raw â€” the backend re-derives `fields` at deploy).
const { fields, formFields, issues, valid } = projectFormSchema(schema);
//    fields     â†’ live field inventory (preview of what the Go parser derives)
//    formFields â†’ ApprovalFlowEditor plugins.formFields (condition / permission editors)
//    valid      â†’ gate persistence on it; errors are contract-breaking

// 3. Save-time gate (structural validateSchema + projection in one pass).
const gate = validateApprovalSchema(candidate, registries);
```

## Projection rules

- Only root-scope keyed nodes project; both device presentations are walked (pc wins a key collision,
  mobile-only fields still project â€” the backend's form data is a closed contract).
- A subform becomes a single-level `table` field: template leaves are its columns, layout containers in
  the template are transparent, a nested subform is an error. `minRows` / `maxRows` map to
  `validation.minLength` / `maxLength` (row-count bounds); `minRows >= 1` sets `isRequired`.
- `switch` (boolean) and `daterange` (array) are unprojectable â€” the Go runtime validates `input` /
  `date` values as strings â€” and raise error issues. Unknown keyed widget types do too, never a silent drop.
- Options: static (inline or referenced) inline into `options`; remote sources omit `options` with a
  warning â€” the backend then accepts any submitted value.
- `columnType` is emitted from the explicit designer override, else from `inferColumnType` â€” EXCEPT a
  precision-less number, which stays ungated (no columnType): the backend enforces `integer` at submit
  time regardless of storage mode, so auto-inferring it would reject every fractional value. Configure a
  `precision` (â†’ `decimal` + `scale`) or pin the type explicitly when you want the gate.
- A `pattern` using constructs RE2 does not support (lookahead / lookbehind / backreferences) is an
  error: JS accepts them, the Go deploy rejects them.
- Cross-device conflicts on a shared key are errors when they break the submit contract: different
  projected kinds, or a detail table whose column sets differ. Same-kind divergence in options /
  validation between devices is NOT detected (pc wins silently) â€” keep those aligned by hand.
- Linkage does not survive projection (warning): a linkage-hidden field's value is dropped from the
  submit payload, which can conflict with a static `isRequired`.
- Under `table` storage the backend additionally constrains field keys at deploy time (reserved column
  names such as `id` / `instance_id` / `row_index` / `created_at`, case-insensitive uniqueness, â‰¤63
  chars, no leading digit). The bridge does not pre-check these â€” it cannot know the storage mode.
- `defaultValue` and `props` are declared on the contract but never emitted today (no designer source /
  no consumer) â€” they are the extension points for host-enriched definitions.
